<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-782-292  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 782 292.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  August 1990 v63 n8 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big numbers? Not here. (Siemens's GaAlAs laser is long onefficiency, power economy, and durability) (gallium aluminumarsenide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gosch, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Siemens AG's gallium aluminum arsenide (GaAlAs) laser diode forsmall-signal optical transmission consumes little power and isefficient and inexpensive, but it could easily be fabricated inlarge volume.andP;  The laser has a bandwidth of 14 GHz and awavelength of about 830 nanometers (nm), and consumes only 60milliwatts (mW) to produce 10 mW of optical power.andP;  The laser'sefficiency is 0.4 mW per milliamp (mA) at 10 to 15 mA thresholdcurrents.andP;  The laser can achieve bandwidths over 10 GHz attemperatures up to 80 degrees centigrade, making it useful forcomputer applications.andP;  The laser could be used in opticalcomputers or for short-range signal transmission betweencomputers.andP;  The laser uses a ridge waveguide structure, composedof 'quantum wells' in an active zone consisting of three 7.5 nmgallium arsenide (GaAs) layers separated by two 8 nm GaAlAslayers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Siemens AG (product development).andO;Ticker:    SIEMN.andO;Topic:     Gallium arsenide semiconductorsLasersProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The gallium aluminum arsenide laser's active zone structure.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>